<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="663" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[168,777,495,687]" pageId="12" pageNumber="663">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,457,495,519]" pageId="12" pageNumber="663">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[462,570,495,519]" name="Colombia" pageId="12" pageNumber="663">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[580,701,495,519]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="12" pageNumber="663">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry name="Ecuador" pageId="12" pageNumber="663">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[265,354,529,552]" name="Panama" pageId="12" pageNumber="663">Panama</collectingCountry>
. On Cerro Pirre this species generally grows in cloud forests, which are located above 
<quantity box="[689,773,562,586]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="663" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
. This species frequently presents terrestrial habit, but in places with abundant humidity and mosses, it can grow as an epiphyte.
</paragraph>
